00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:32.500
And one person during
one of the conversations

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:34.375
said something that I
thought was brilliant,

00:02:34.375 --> 00:02:36.250
and so I decided I should
put it in the book.

00:02:36.250 --> 00:02:38.304
And I made the mistake
of putting it at the end.

00:02:38.304 --> 00:02:40.220
And I say it was a mistake
because it's really

00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:42.178
sort of the guiding thesis
for the entire book,

00:02:42.178 --> 00:02:45.350
and it's this-- great leaders
don't innovate the product,

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:47.000
they innovate the factory.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.530
And I realize how
dangerous it is to say that

00:02:49.530 --> 00:02:51.716
at a place like this, right?

00:02:51.716 --> 00:02:53.840
But what I mean is that
innovations to the factory,

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:56.940
factory being a metaphor
for all of our workplaces,

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:59.750
precede innovations
to the products.

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:02.690
The innovations that we make to
how we work and where we work

00:03:02.690 --> 00:03:05.570
precede our ability to innovate
in any other situation.

00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:07.470
And this has been true
for hundreds of years.

00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:11.030
This was true when a
young junior consultant

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:12.780
first approached
Bethlehem Steel and said,

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:13.910
I can turn around your problem.

00:03:13.910 --> 00:03:15.951
Now, you probably never
heard of Bethlehem Steel.

00:03:15.951 --> 00:03:16.580
That's OK.

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:19.050
But their impact resonated
for hundreds of years.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:20.600
See, this young
junior consultant

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:22.790
wanted to help
Bethlehem Steel compete

00:03:22.790 --> 00:03:24.390
with bigger captains
of industry,

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:27.090
like Carnegie Steel and a
variety of different places.

00:03:27.090 --> 00:03:28.970
And so he came with
what would later

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:32.240
be his world-renown stopwatch.

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:35.220
And he begin to study the
production process at Bethlehem

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:38.600
Steel, and he begin to find
the optimal way to design

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:39.850
that production process.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:42.060
And then he started
training the labor force

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:45.770
on how to conform to
that one best way.

00:03:45.770 --> 00:03:48.730
And he revolutionized the
entire history of manufacturing.

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:51.780
He made it possible in the
early 1900s for a variety

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:53.384
of different industrial growth.

00:03:53.384 --> 00:03:54.800
Some of you are
nodding your heads

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:56.070
because you've
figured out who it is.

00:03:56.070 --> 00:03:57.611
But if you haven't
yet, I'll give you

00:03:57.611 --> 00:03:59.950
a famous quote that
sort of embodies

00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:03.090
what he believed about the
role of management and labor.

00:04:03.090 --> 00:04:05.020
And it was this--
"The duty of enforcing

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:07.490
the adoption of standards and
enforcing this cooperation

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:08.770
rests with management alone."

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:11.050
He was big on the idea
that you had management

00:04:11.050 --> 00:04:13.510
and you had labor, and it was
best to keep the two separate

00:04:13.510 --> 00:04:15.580
because labor was
too dumb to know how

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:17.180
to do something the right way.

00:04:17.180 --> 00:04:19.690
So it was management's job
to teach them how to do it,

00:04:19.690 --> 00:04:22.019
labor's job to just do it.

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:24.600
This man was Frederick
Winslow Taylor.

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:26.720
How many of you remember
Frederick Winslow Taylor?

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:28.780
So I teach undergraduate
management classes.

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:31.320
And so we have to spend, like,
the first two weeks talking

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:33.710
about the amazing contribution
of Frederick Taylor,

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:36.547
and also why he
was totally wrong.

00:04:36.547 --> 00:04:38.630
Frederick Taylor was
definitely right for his era.

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:41.200
He knew that you had to
reinvent the factory in order

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:43.450
to have all of the
innovations we needed to grow.

00:04:43.450 --> 00:04:45.450
That was very true,
and his impact

00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:46.826
resonated for a
really long time.

00:04:46.826 --> 00:04:49.408
Taylor would write a book called
"The Principles of Scientific

00:04:49.408 --> 00:04:51.090
Management" that
is still in print.

00:04:51.090 --> 00:04:52.199
It's been over 100 years.

00:04:52.199 --> 00:04:53.740
"Principles of
Scientific Management"

00:04:53.740 --> 00:04:54.610
would travel the globe.

00:04:54.610 --> 00:04:56.734
It would be translated into
a variety of languages.

00:04:56.734 --> 00:04:59.750
Actually, Taylor's
grandson remarked one time

00:04:59.750 --> 00:05:01.580
that he went to Japan
to visit executives

00:05:01.580 --> 00:05:03.870
and they bowed
very deeply to him

00:05:03.870 --> 00:05:07.290
just because he was the
grandson of Frederick Taylor.

00:05:07.290 --> 00:05:08.957
Taylor's devotees
would start a magazine

00:05:08.957 --> 00:05:11.290
about scientific management
that would morph and change,

00:05:11.290 --> 00:05:13.300
and you know it now as
"Bloomberg Businessweek."

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:16.830
It got its start as a
fanzine for Frederick Taylor.

00:05:16.830 --> 00:05:19.272
He also joined the faculty
at Tuck, Dartmouth's business

00:05:19.272 --> 00:05:20.980
school, one of the
first business schools

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:22.096
in the country.

00:05:22.096 --> 00:05:24.220
And he revolutionized
Bethlehem Steel and a variety

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:25.220
of different industries.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:28.600
We got where we are
right now because of what

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:31.520
Frederick Taylor did in
the physical factories.

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:34.290
But where we are right now
is not the physical factory,

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:35.340
doesn't look like it.

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:38.500
I have not been to many
actual manufacturing plants

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:40.060
with food that's good.

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.580
So it is not a physical factory.

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:46.120
We've moved from a physical
factory to an idea factory.

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:49.260
The products usually
aren't made by brute force.

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:52.300
The unit of energy or where it
lies is not the bicep anymore.

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:53.534
It's the brain.

00:05:53.534 --> 00:05:54.700
We designed it in our heads.

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:58.230
We moved from a physical
factory to an idea factory.

00:05:58.230 --> 00:06:00.400
But we drug Frederick
Taylor with us

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:02.440
from the factory to the office.

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:06.310
And a lot of the ideas inside
of management theorists

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:09.479
are based in Frederick
Taylor's theories.

00:06:09.479 --> 00:06:11.770
He's the foundation for almost
all management thinking.

00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:13.770
And while we point to
things-- Peter Drucker was

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:15.520
the first to do it--
we point to things

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:17.570
that signal to shift
from industrial work

00:06:17.570 --> 00:06:19.809
to the knowledge economy,
we don't necessarily

00:06:19.809 --> 00:06:21.600
point to the things
that we should probably

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:22.781
have not taken with us.

00:06:22.781 --> 00:06:24.280
And so today, I
want to talk briefly

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:26.615
about a lot of those
different things.

00:06:26.615 --> 00:06:27.990
I've surveyed the
Googlers that I

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:30.280
know about what would
be controversial but not

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:32.642
too controversial because
a lot of these ideas,

00:06:32.642 --> 00:06:34.600
I find that everybody,
every innovative company

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:36.391
I've spoke at, is either
doing some of them

00:06:36.391 --> 00:06:38.130
or deliberately
not doing others.

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:39.880
And so we'll have that
conversation, which

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:41.290
I think will be a lot of fun.

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:43.400
But I want to start
with one that's probably

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:45.250
not one of the things
you think about,

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:47.390
even though it's so vital
to our work every day.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:48.848
And when you do
you think about it,

00:06:48.848 --> 00:06:51.320
you may not have very
positive thoughts.

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:53.126
I want to talk about email.

00:06:53.126 --> 00:06:55.500
And I realize I'm speaking to
the group that power, like,

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:57.880
half the world's email.

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:01.430
And so I don't want to
tell you you're wrong,

00:07:01.430 --> 00:07:03.909
but I do want to join with
you in saying how many of you

00:07:03.909 --> 00:07:05.200
actually hate your email inbox?

00:07:08.204 --> 00:07:09.870
And the Gmail inbox
is one of the better

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:12.699
ones for dealing with the
problem of email, right?

00:07:12.699 --> 00:07:15.240
Everybody's making note on who
raised their hand, by the way.

00:07:15.240 --> 00:07:16.610
It's kind of funny.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:18.485
Everybody's looking
around-- who hates email?

00:07:18.485 --> 00:07:20.000
Email is an amazing tool.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:21.700
It's an amazing invention.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:23.610
And like most
amazing inventions,

00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:27.850
we're using it for stuff it
was never designed to do.

00:07:27.850 --> 00:07:29.810
How many of you use
it as a to-do list?

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:32.060
How many of you have ever
said the phrase, if it's not

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:35.149
in my inbox, it won't get done?

00:07:35.149 --> 00:07:37.190
This was not what it was
originally intended for.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:40.681
And we have this idea that--
actually, here's another one.

00:07:40.681 --> 00:07:42.430
This is probably I'm
guilty of doing this,

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:43.737
and I wrote this chapter.

00:07:43.737 --> 00:07:45.320
How many of you have
ever cleared out,

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:46.805
gotten to inbox
zero, and thought,

00:07:46.805 --> 00:07:49.300
wow, I had a really
productive day today?

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:51.740
And then you're driving home
or you're taking the T home

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:54.430
and you're like, oh, actually,
I didn't do anything today

00:07:54.430 --> 00:07:56.600
except respond to email?

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:59.510
So we have this theory that
it equals productivity,

00:07:59.510 --> 00:08:01.280
but it's an inverted U.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:03.907
And a lot of places are finding
that it is that exact inverted

00:08:03.907 --> 00:08:06.240
U, that productivity can go
up through the communication

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:08.040
and collaboration
that it allows for,

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:10.354
but it can also go
dramatically down.

00:08:10.354 --> 00:08:11.770
And one company
in particular that

00:08:11.770 --> 00:08:13.890
fascinated me was
a French company

00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:15.890
called Atos, a
technology company

00:08:15.890 --> 00:08:18.700
that basically said our
productivity is not happening

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:19.880
the way we want it to.

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:22.300
And so led by their
CEO, they moved

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:27.050
to become a zero-email
company, zero internal email.

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:30.000
They created a variety of
different products and tools

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.419
in order to use
communication tools.

00:08:32.419 --> 00:08:34.460
It's actually kind of
weird that I'm sitting here

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.370
talking about this
because when people ask me

00:08:36.370 --> 00:08:38.120
what my favorite tool
to replace email is,

00:08:38.120 --> 00:08:39.871
I tell them Google Wave.

00:08:39.871 --> 00:08:41.314
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:41.314 --> 00:08:43.080
I loved it.

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:44.049
Can I just say that?

00:08:44.049 --> 00:08:46.470
I loved it.

00:08:46.470 --> 00:08:47.920
Apparently, other people didn't.

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:49.480
But I thought it was brilliant.

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:52.000
So maybe this is where we
start bringing that back,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:53.845
with this idea that
let's replace-- anyway,

00:08:53.845 --> 00:08:55.720
so they moved to become
a zero-email company.

00:08:55.720 --> 00:08:57.320
They custom-designed
a tool for them.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:08:59.770
But a lot of other companies
are finding the same thing.

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:02.670
And they're using old-school
tools like the phone,

00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:05.690
or like getting up
out of their desk

00:09:05.690 --> 00:09:07.550
and walking over and
having a conversation.

00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:08.300
It's fascinating.

00:09:08.300 --> 00:09:11.804
But the idea that all of
these share is that email

00:09:11.804 --> 00:09:13.720
has a variety of different
costs and benefits,

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:17.000
and the costs are beginning
to not outweigh the benefits.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.200
So Atos moved to become
a zero-email company.

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:21.500
They're still moving to
become a zero-email company.

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:22.780
They're not quite there yet.

00:09:22.780 --> 00:09:25.550
But they have found that
as email's going down,

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:28.140
a variety of positives
are happening.

00:09:28.140 --> 00:09:29.682
Their operating
margin has increased.

00:09:29.682 --> 00:09:31.348
Their earnings per
share have increased.

00:09:31.348 --> 00:09:33.060
Their administrative
costs have decreased

00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:34.685
because, again,
there's just less email

00:09:34.685 --> 00:09:35.720
to have to sort through.

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:37.365
It's been a really
good thing for them,

00:09:37.365 --> 00:09:39.115
and they've become
advocates for this sort

00:09:39.115 --> 00:09:41.217
of zero-email lifestyle.

00:09:41.217 --> 00:09:43.550
But honestly, how many of you
are sitting here thinking,

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:47.540
there's no way I can do
without my email inbox?

00:09:47.540 --> 00:09:48.080
I like it.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:50.637
I use it as my to-do
list, et cetera.

00:09:50.637 --> 00:09:51.970
You have to see what I just saw.

00:09:51.970 --> 00:09:54.350
I saw a bunch of people
looking down and then

00:09:54.350 --> 00:09:57.020
holding their hand up, like
I'm embarrassed to say.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:09:57.770
I'm with you, too.

00:09:57.770 --> 00:09:59.440
I can't find a way
to do without it.

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:03.150
But there are ways that
we can put buffers on it.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:06.200
There are other policies
besides zero-email.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:08.410
We have limited email,
which is saying that we only

00:10:08.410 --> 00:10:09.510
email at certain times.

00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:11.890
So there's a dedicated
time for the email blitz,

00:10:11.890 --> 00:10:14.214
and then you focus in
on doing the deep work.

00:10:14.214 --> 00:10:15.630
And then there's
work hours email.

00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:17.300
One of my favorite
corporate examples

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:21.310
is a company literally shuts
the server off at 6:00 PM.

