So if you want to take your
laptop home with you, if you're

00:10:23.910 --> 00:10:27.170
that person that everybody knows
who you are because you like

00:10:27.170 --> 00:10:29.380
to email at 11:30
at night, you're

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:31.220
that person, that's
totally cool.

00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:33.990
We just won't get your emails
until 8:00 AM the next morning

00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:36.050
when the server comes back on.

00:10:36.050 --> 00:10:38.480
What all of these have
in common is two things--

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:40.900
the idea of allowing people
to design their workday

00:10:40.900 --> 00:10:42.770
in a way that works for them.

00:10:42.770 --> 00:10:45.060
Email's an amazing
tool because it's cheap

00:10:45.060 --> 00:10:45.990
and it's asynchronous.

00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:48.170
It's cheap to send, and
we send a lot of it.

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:50.970
And it's asynchronous, so we
can send it whenever we want.

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:52.850
But what we don't
think about is the fact

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:56.090
that that means people receive
it whenever we want to send it,

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:58.090
which means that it's
great that you can take it

00:10:58.090 --> 00:11:00.280
and you can use it to
design your perfect workday,

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:01.655
but your perfect
workday butts up

00:11:01.655 --> 00:11:03.720
against other people's
ability to design

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:04.920
their perfect workday.

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:07.010
And we've never had
this conversation.

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:10.130
And you may begin to
become a champion for zero

00:11:10.130 --> 00:11:11.450
or limited hours of work.

00:11:11.450 --> 00:11:13.230
That's honestly not the point.

00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:17.260
The point is we've never had
a conversation about what

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:20.110
is the right communication
tool for our project, what

00:11:20.110 --> 00:11:22.510
is the right communication
tool for our team,

00:11:22.510 --> 00:11:25.139
and then what are our
own individual limits?

00:11:25.139 --> 00:11:26.930
I've talked with a lot
of different people,

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:31.090
mostly subordinates who report
to a manager who likes to email

00:11:31.090 --> 00:11:32.960
at 10:00, 11:00 at night.

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:35.340
And even though they
know they don't have to,

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:36.870
there's always that
subtle pressure

00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:38.930
that you have to
respond quickly.

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:41.807
And we've never had that
open and frank conversation.

00:11:41.807 --> 00:11:44.140
So whether it's zero email,
whether it's outlawing email

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:45.430
entirely, or whether
it's actually

00:11:45.430 --> 00:11:47.096
having a conversation
with your team of,

00:11:47.096 --> 00:11:49.710
hey, what is the best way to
communicate and collaborate,

00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:51.940
which tool do we
want to use, we can

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:54.060
see a lot of
positive effects just

00:11:54.060 --> 00:11:56.130
from taking a deep look
at how we collaborate,

00:11:56.130 --> 00:11:58.300
how we communicate.

00:11:58.300 --> 00:12:00.310
I want to move into
one of my favorites.

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:03.152
This comes from HCL
Technologies based out of India,

00:12:03.152 --> 00:12:05.110
but it's this idea of
putting customers second.

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:08.510
Now, I know that
the Boston location

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:10.790
has a variety of the
sales team, a variety

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:14.836
of different Googlers,
and this idea in sales

00:12:14.836 --> 00:12:16.210
that the customer's
always right.

00:12:16.210 --> 00:12:17.550
How many of you
have ever said that?

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:19.060
How you ever been the
customer and invoked that?

00:12:19.060 --> 00:12:19.707
That's when you hear it.

00:12:19.707 --> 00:12:22.248
Do you ever notice you always
hear it then, customer's always

00:12:22.248 --> 00:12:24.040
right when you're the customer?

00:12:24.040 --> 00:12:26.260
And, of course, you pull
that line and somebody says

00:12:26.260 --> 00:12:28.570
or somebody wants to
say in their head, like,

00:12:28.570 --> 00:12:31.210
but you're totally
wrong in this instance,

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:32.850
but I have pretend
that you're right?

00:12:32.850 --> 00:12:34.891
So what is this idea of
putting customers second?

00:12:34.891 --> 00:12:37.530
It's essentially this
idea that in order

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:40.760
to move customer
loyalty, you have

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:42.050
to look at what creates it.

00:12:42.050 --> 00:12:43.020
It's not a goal.

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:45.920
It's an effect, and we have
to look at what the cause is.

00:12:45.920 --> 00:12:49.110
Customer loyalty is created
inside of a value zone.

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:50.926
And to explain how
a value zone works,

00:12:50.926 --> 00:12:52.300
let's dive deep
on the org chart.

00:12:52.300 --> 00:12:53.490
And this isn't all that deep.

00:12:53.490 --> 00:12:55.198
It's actually only a
few boxes and lines.

00:12:55.198 --> 00:12:57.890
But already, you can visualize
what your own reporting

00:12:57.890 --> 00:13:00.070
relationships have
ever looked like.

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:01.950
What happens in almost
every company that

00:13:01.950 --> 00:13:05.420
has ever been started has
a founder or founders.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:08.570
And as the organization scales,
generally those founders

00:13:08.570 --> 00:13:10.840
move up through the ranks.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.210
So naturally, as you're
teaching other people

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:16.870
how to do what you used to
do and you now outsource

00:13:16.870 --> 00:13:20.000
to another person, either inside
the company or outside of it,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.830
you want to keep that person
informed and accountable.

00:13:22.830 --> 00:13:26.360
So most org charts work that
way-- information flows down,

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:27.372
accountability flows up.

00:13:27.372 --> 00:13:29.830
The front line is accountable
to the management structures,

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:31.220
et cetera.

00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:33.370
And in HCL Technologies,
Vineet Nayar, the CEO,

00:13:33.370 --> 00:13:36.700
basically said, where's
the value being created,

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:38.736
because most of the
times in customer loyalty

00:13:38.736 --> 00:13:40.270
and in customer
satisfaction, the value's

00:13:40.270 --> 00:13:41.978
not being created at
the place that we're

00:13:41.978 --> 00:13:43.290
holding people accountable to.

00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:46.780
So we created what he sort
of termed the value zone,

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:49.440
and the value zone was
that place where people

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:50.974
interact with the customer.

00:13:50.974 --> 00:13:53.140
If you're in a role that
interacts with the customer

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:55.370
or you have an activity that
interacts with the customer,

00:13:55.370 --> 00:13:56.453
you are in the value zone.

00:13:56.453 --> 00:13:59.500
You're the one
creating the value.

00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:01.450
And so we have to think
about this information

00:14:01.450 --> 00:14:03.630
and accountability thing as
it pertains to the value zone

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.713
because most of the time,
people in the value zone

00:14:05.713 --> 00:14:06.770
have a divided loyalty.

00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:08.670
The customer's
always right, but I

00:14:08.670 --> 00:14:11.180
have to get my boss
whatever she needs.

00:14:11.180 --> 00:14:14.730
And that creates a divided
loyalty that can cause tension.

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.432
And in some fields,
we've even seen it--

00:14:16.432 --> 00:14:18.473
I will not ask you to
raise your hand on this one

00:14:18.473 --> 00:14:21.120
because you may not want to--
but we've even seen situations

00:14:21.120 --> 00:14:22.620
where in order to
please a customer,

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:24.580
the person who used to
be serving that customer

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:26.600
is thrown under the bus
so the management can

00:14:26.600 --> 00:14:28.740
come in and solve the problem.

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.610
And what does that
do future for wanting

00:14:30.610 --> 00:14:31.870
to continue to
create value, wanting

00:14:31.870 --> 00:14:33.161
to continue to serve customers?

00:14:33.161 --> 00:14:34.960
It doesn't really
help all that much.

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:36.850
And so what HCL
did was essentially

00:14:36.850 --> 00:14:39.050
turn their entire org
chart upside-down.

00:14:39.050 --> 00:14:40.930
They reversed that
accountability

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:43.250
and they built in
extra transparency.

00:14:43.250 --> 00:14:45.339
What reverse the
accountability means

00:14:45.339 --> 00:14:47.630
is they turned the org chart
upside-down and they said,

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:49.671
we in the management and
in the support functions

00:14:49.671 --> 00:14:51.120
are accountable
to the value zone.

00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:53.600
Wherever the value zone is
and as we change our business

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:56.990
model, wherever it goes, we need
to be accountable to it, even

00:14:56.990 --> 00:15:00.280
to the point of creating a
customer service ticket system

00:15:00.280 --> 00:15:01.600
for people in the value zone.

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:02.837
So you're serving a customer.

00:15:02.837 --> 00:15:05.170
There is the normal sort of
customer complaint, customer

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:06.850
satisfaction ticket system.

00:15:06.850 --> 00:15:09.132
They use a similar one
for I'm in the value zone

00:15:09.132 --> 00:15:11.090
and I need something and
I've got to figure out

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:12.191
where it comes from.

00:15:12.191 --> 00:15:13.690
We create a customer
support ticket.

00:15:13.690 --> 00:15:16.440
And only the person in the value
zone who created that ticket

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:17.700
can close it.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:20.140
And managers are actually
rated and bonused

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:21.729
on how well are
you serving these,

00:15:21.729 --> 00:15:23.520
how well are you closing
out these tickets,

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:24.940
how well are you getting
these people what they need.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:26.815
So it's this idea, again,
that accountability

00:15:26.815 --> 00:15:28.716
rests in the value zone.

00:15:28.716 --> 00:15:30.466
Transparency took a
real interesting form.

00:15:30.466 --> 00:15:35.040
And in the HR world, we love
to talk about 360 feedback.

00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:39.520
But what we usually mean by that
is manager, peers, and a couple

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:41.185
of hand-picked subordinates.

00:15:41.185 --> 00:15:42.560
They went a step
further and they

00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:45.980
said that every single person
that interacts with you

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:48.820
has a right to give you
feedback and has a right

00:15:48.820 --> 00:15:51.820
to see the feedback you're
getting from other places,

00:15:51.820 --> 00:15:54.210
extending out this idea of
transparency of feedback,

00:15:54.210 --> 00:15:56.280
extending out this
idea of accountability

00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:58.550
to that value zone.

00:15:58.550 --> 00:16:00.260
And the results were
pretty incredible.

00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:03.640
I don't think you have
to dive too deep into it,

00:16:03.640 --> 00:16:05.790
but I want to explain why
they were so incredible.

00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:08.552
So we have, again, this
idea that customer loyalty

00:16:08.552 --> 00:16:10.760
is what we're striving for,
customer loyalty predicts

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:11.630
profitability.

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:14.060
And that's true--
increased market share,

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:18.160
increased profits are generally
tied into customer loyalty.

00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:20.290
But customer loyalty
is an effect.

00:16:20.290 --> 00:16:21.550
It's not a cause.

00:16:21.550 --> 00:16:24.600
It comes after certain
other conditions are met.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:27.320
Mainly, we have what we call
the service profit chain,

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:29.410
that customer loyalty
drives profits.

00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:30.050
We know this.

00:16:30.050 --> 00:16:32.360
Profits come from
customer loyalty.

00:16:32.360 --> 00:16:34.090
Customer loyalty
is most strongly

00:16:34.090 --> 00:16:36.429
predicted by employee
satisfaction.

00:16:36.429 --> 00:16:37.720
That's why the food is so good.

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:40.090
It's most strongly predicted
by employee satisfaction,

00:16:40.090 --> 00:16:42.590
and that's most strongly
predicted by designing your org

00:16:42.590 --> 00:16:45.390
chart in a way to figure out
what that value zone is and put

00:16:45.390 --> 00:16:46.210
those people first.

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:48.110
And by the way, you
may not be able to do

00:16:48.110 --> 00:16:49.760
this with an entire
organization,

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:52.500
but you can still do it in
whatever function you serve.

00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:54.000
Who is our customer
for our team?

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.054
Who is our customer for
our broader department?

00:16:56.054 --> 00:16:57.720
How do we best serve
them, and how do we

00:16:57.720 --> 00:16:59.595
make ourselves accountable
to the people that

00:16:59.595 --> 00:17:01.411
service that customer?

00:17:01.411 --> 00:17:02.910
And what I think
is most interesting

00:17:02.910 --> 00:17:05.740
about this is this not an
idea that's all that new.

00:17:05.740 --> 00:17:07.782
The service profit
chain has been around

00:17:07.782 --> 00:17:09.740
for a really long time,
developed by professors

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:11.573
who basically study on
the side of the river

00:17:11.573 --> 00:17:13.109
and on the other
side of the river.

00:17:13.109 --> 00:17:15.700
And we've been advocating
this for a long time.

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:17.730
But often, people
aren't willing to take

00:17:17.730 --> 00:17:20.109
that flip the org chart
mentality, that value zone

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:21.839
mentality.

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:24.400
And what I think HCL
provides us is an opportunity

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:26.130
to look at exactly
what happens when

00:17:26.130 --> 00:17:28.786
we put that value zone first
and we say that, you know what?

00:17:28.786 --> 00:17:30.160
The customer may
always be right.

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:32.340
But in order to make
the customer right,

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:34.340
we have to put our
own people first.

00:17:34.340 --> 00:17:37.660
And we see this in a couple
different companies throughout,

00:17:37.660 --> 00:17:40.930
but there are sort of these
bright stars of employees

00:17:40.930 --> 00:17:41.550
first.

00:17:41.550 --> 00:17:44.091
One of my favorite ones is Danny
Meyer, founder of-- how many

00:17:44.091 --> 00:17:45.570
of you like Shake Shack?

00:17:45.570 --> 00:17:46.990
Yes, yes, yes.

00:17:46.990 --> 00:17:48.340
Awesome.

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:50.200
I was in New York
earlier this week

00:17:50.200 --> 00:17:53.420
and was making a point to go to
every Union Square restaurant

00:17:53.420 --> 00:17:55.644
that I could go to because
the service is amazing

00:17:55.644 --> 00:17:57.060
and I wanted to
see it for myself.

00:17:57.060 --> 00:17:58.768
Danny Meyer, the
founder of Union Square,

00:17:58.768 --> 00:18:01.530
basically says this about
the service-- he sums up

00:18:01.530 --> 00:18:03.990
the service profit chain in
a restaurant-oriented quote--

00:18:03.990 --> 00:18:05.448
"The interests of
our own employees

00:18:05.448 --> 00:18:07.817
must be placed directly
ahead of those of our guests

00:18:07.817 --> 00:18:10.150
because the only way we can
consistently earn raves, win

00:18:10.150 --> 00:18:13.120
repeat business, develop bonds
of loyalty with our guests

00:18:13.120 --> 00:18:15.310
is to first ensure that
our own team members feel

00:18:15.310 --> 00:18:17.220
jazzed about coming to work."

00:18:17.220 --> 00:18:19.860
One of my other favorite
ones is from Howard Schultz

00:18:19.860 --> 00:18:21.219
of Starbucks.

00:18:21.219 --> 00:18:23.593
Howard Schultz, if you're
unfamiliar the Starbucks story,

00:18:23.593 --> 00:18:26.951
you know that Howard Schultz
grew it to its notoriety

00:18:26.951 --> 00:18:29.450
and then stepped back from the
CEO role, just a new chairman

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:31.800
role, and a lot
of things changed.

00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:33.550
The changes were
subtle at first,

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:36.070
but you could
eventually taste them.

00:18:36.070 --> 00:18:37.697
And so Schultz
decided to come back,

00:18:37.697 --> 00:18:39.280
needed to turn the
stock price around.

00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:42.000
And so one of the biggest things
that a lot of the investors

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.790
were arguing for
was, Howard, you

00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:46.266
can cut the health
insurance plan.

00:18:46.266 --> 00:18:48.140
You're trying to turn
the stock price around.

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:49.850
Nobody will blame you for that.

00:18:49.850 --> 00:18:51.865
They'll understand
that you need to do it.

00:18:51.865 --> 00:18:53.700
And he said, you know what?

00:18:53.700 --> 00:18:55.630
You should probably
sell your stock

00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:57.240
because we're not
going to do that.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:58.150
Why?

00:18:58.150 --> 00:19:00.510
Because I do not believe
that shareholder value

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:02.470
is sustainable if you're
not creating value

00:19:02.470 --> 00:19:04.640
for the people who
are doing the work.

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:09.270
Again, we see business leaders
summarizing in their own ways

00:19:09.270 --> 00:19:11.940
and in their own stories
a service profit chain

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:13.920
idea that's been around
for a really long time.

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:15.461
It made me most
excited to see-- this

00:19:15.461 --> 00:19:18.220
is one of those ideas in the
book, again, that's not new,

00:19:18.220 --> 00:19:19.830
but is an example
of what it means

00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:23.410
to up-end business as usual.

00:19:23.410 --> 00:19:25.064
I asked a bunch of
different people

00:19:25.064 --> 00:19:26.980
which chapter in the
book I should talk about,

00:19:26.980 --> 00:19:28.700
and they all said this one.

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:31.701
And I was not planning
on talking about it,

00:19:31.701 --> 00:19:33.200
but I do think that
most people want

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:35.660
to hear either why their office
is amazing or why it's not.

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:37.830
So shall we dive into it?

00:19:37.830 --> 00:19:40.540
So does anybody
know, by curiosity,

00:19:40.540 --> 00:19:43.791
where the trend towards
open offices started?

00:19:43.791 --> 00:19:44.290
No.

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:46.130
You know why?

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:48.840
I'll give you where
it started, but we

00:19:48.840 --> 00:19:51.760
like to conveniently forget
that it started here.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:53.340
It actually started
with Jay Chiat

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:55.180
and Chiat/Day advertising.

00:19:55.180 --> 00:19:57.790
If you've ever seen the famous
1984 commercial throwing

00:19:57.790 --> 00:19:59.586
the hammer through the
big brother screen,

00:19:59.586 --> 00:20:00.710
that was developed by them.

00:20:00.710 --> 00:20:02.560
And they had this
revolutionary idea

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:06.740
of creating the first open
office, totally nomadic office.

00:20:06.740 --> 00:20:08.710
You got a locker
and a laptop and you

00:20:08.710 --> 00:20:10.680
got to find your own place.

00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:15.160
And it was a brilliant
idea in theory.

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:16.980
And they spent
millions of dollars

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:19.980
transforming their office
space, and it became a disaster.

00:20:19.980 --> 00:20:21.750
My favorite stories
out of it is you

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:24.870
had people who would
arrive at work at 4:00 AM

00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:27.450
and put their laptop
down to claim a desk

00:20:27.450 --> 00:20:29.780
and then go back to their
car and sleep for a few hours

00:20:29.780 --> 00:20:33.360
so they could come back and
get their favorite place.

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:35.440
You had people cramming
stuff into lockers

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:38.670
because you could have no,
like, tchotchkes whatsoever,

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:41.170
no personal flair,
no symbols of what

00:20:41.170 --> 00:20:42.910
you were about in that space.

00:20:42.910 --> 00:20:44.510
You had to have
them in your locker.

00:20:44.510 --> 00:20:46.700
One woman couldn't
actually fit everything

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:48.800
she needed to do her
job in the locker.

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:51.180
So she became known
as the red wagon lady

00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:53.634
because she would pull
around a little red wagon

00:20:53.634 --> 00:20:54.550
with all of her stuff.

00:20:54.550 --> 00:20:57.130
This was before we started
doing those crates and the bags

00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:59.310
with wheels and
whatever, which speaking

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:00.920
of innovative
products, I still don't

00:21:00.920 --> 00:21:04.055
know why it took so long to
figure out wheels on bags.

00:21:04.055 --> 00:21:05.930
But this happened before
we figured that out,

00:21:05.930 --> 00:21:09.250
and she became the
little red wagon lady.

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:12.120
What happens essentially
with the open office is this.

00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:14.296
First of all, there's
this whole conversation

00:21:14.296 --> 00:21:16.670
about whether or not people
are introverts and extroverts

00:21:16.670 --> 00:21:17.890
and what they actually want.

00:21:17.890 --> 00:21:20.080
And let me kill this
for you right now.

00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:23.040
Introversion and extroversion
is a sliding scale,

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:25.245
and every single person
is different on it.

00:21:25.245 --> 00:21:26.870
If you take a Big
Five test, you're all

00:21:26.870 --> 00:21:27.730
going to get different numbers.

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:29.690
You're very rarely
placed into that box.

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:33.210
And so the idea that we
can find one perfect place

00:21:33.210 --> 00:21:39.350
for you is foolish
because what you need

00:21:39.350 --> 00:21:40.810
varies by the type
of work you do

00:21:40.810 --> 00:21:42.810
and how you would score on that.

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:45.290
But even looking company-wide,
there's a balance,

00:21:45.290 --> 00:21:46.990
there's a trade-off.

00:21:46.990 --> 00:21:52.130
The research in
favor of open offices

00:21:52.130 --> 00:21:54.440
will say things like, oh,
it increases collaboration,

00:21:54.440 --> 00:21:57.070
it increases creativity,
there's these serendipitous

00:21:57.070 --> 00:21:58.520
experiences.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:00.810
And so it's for those benefits.

00:22:00.810 --> 00:22:04.570
(WHISPERING) It helps that it's
a lot cheaper, let's just say.

00:22:04.570 --> 00:22:06.330
But then on the
other side, we never

00:22:06.330 --> 00:22:07.869
really talk about these studies.

00:22:07.869 --> 00:22:09.410
The studies show
that people are more

00:22:09.410 --> 00:22:11.642
likely to experience
stress, especially where you

00:22:11.642 --> 00:22:12.600
sit in the open office.

00:22:12.600 --> 00:22:13.960
Have you ever
noticed if you've got

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:16.126
kind of open seating, people
gravitate towards being

00:22:16.126 --> 00:22:18.580
able to put their
back towards the wall?

00:22:18.580 --> 00:22:20.790
That's pretty ancient
in human psychology

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:23.270
and human development,
this idea that we

00:22:23.270 --> 00:22:25.049
need to be able to
see the whole room.

00:22:25.049 --> 00:22:25.590
And we do it.

00:22:25.590 --> 00:22:27.798
And if you're one of the
people who doesn't get that,

00:22:27.798 --> 00:22:30.320
you're actually
experiencing more stress.

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:33.060
In addition, there are
increases in distraction.

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:35.140
Some places have
tried to mitigate this

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:37.080
by having this sort
of earbud code.

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:38.700
Two earbuds in means
don't talk to me.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:39.680
One means ask.

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:41.840
Two means you can come up to me.

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:42.880
Some of you are looking
at me like you've never

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:43.630
heard that before.

00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:45.810
Cool, that might be your
only takeaway from today.

00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:46.780
That's awesome.

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:47.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:47.870 --> 00:22:49.770
And that might have just
super helped, right?

00:22:49.770 --> 00:22:51.894
But we've come up with
that as a response

00:22:51.894 --> 00:22:54.310
to having to sort of cope with
the distraction factor that

00:22:54.310 --> 00:22:55.500
happens in these offices.

00:22:55.500 --> 00:22:58.180
And then my favorite study shows
that people in an open office

00:22:58.180 --> 00:23:00.600
floor plan are more likely
to call in sick to work

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:04.580
more often, which means they're
either legitimately sick more,

00:23:04.580 --> 00:23:07.120
or they're sick of
their open office.

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:09.320
In either case,
again, it comes down

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:13.310
to having a broader conversation
about individual differences.

00:23:13.310 --> 00:23:15.720
And here's the challenge,
and here's the truth.

00:23:15.720 --> 00:23:18.720
The number one factor that
affects office environment--

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:21.000
it's not cool offices,
it's not free food,

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.060
it's not funky design,
although I absolutely

00:23:23.060 --> 00:23:26.170
love the T thing going
on in the elevators.

00:23:26.170 --> 00:23:27.510
That's awesome.

00:23:27.510 --> 00:23:31.152
But the number one factor
that affects employees,

00:23:31.152 --> 00:23:33.110
how environment affects
employees' performance,

00:23:33.110 --> 00:23:35.720
is perceived control--
how much control

00:23:35.720 --> 00:23:39.440
you have to move around, to
change your office as you work

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:42.962
there, and to adjust it to the
needs of when you're working

00:23:42.962 --> 00:23:45.170
with individuals, teams,
when you're doing deep work,

00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:47.070
or when you need that
serendipity-- perceived

00:23:47.070 --> 00:23:47.816
control.

00:23:47.816 --> 00:23:49.190
And so it's really
not a question

00:23:49.190 --> 00:23:51.890
of closing open offices, opening
up closed offices, et cetera,

00:23:51.890 --> 00:23:53.264
but it's that idea
that we should

00:23:53.264 --> 00:23:55.140
start from the
assumption of what

00:23:55.140 --> 00:23:58.110
do I need to do to give
my team perceived control?

00:23:58.110 --> 00:24:00.420
I've been in a lot of
really beautiful offices

00:24:00.420 --> 00:24:03.100
where people aren't even allowed
to change the number of picture

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:05.190
frames on their desk.

00:24:05.190 --> 00:24:08.540
What do you think that
does to perceived control?

00:24:08.540 --> 00:24:11.030
And by the way, this ties in
with a huge stream of research

00:24:11.030 --> 00:24:12.370
around the importance
of autonomy.

00:24:12.370 --> 00:24:14.380
If we're saying we want
to give people autonomy,

00:24:14.380 --> 00:24:15.754
we want to give
people free time,

00:24:15.754 --> 00:24:19.240
we give people the ability to
control how they do their work

00:24:19.240 --> 00:24:21.880
but we don't let them control
where they do their work,

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:25.090
then we're giving them false
promises about autonomy.

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:29.789
One of my favorite office
design, a lot of people

00:24:29.789 --> 00:24:31.330
have a lot of
different terms for it.

00:24:31.330 --> 00:24:34.940
My favorite term for it is
creating a palette of places,

00:24:34.940 --> 00:24:37.450
creating a palette of
places where people can

00:24:37.450 --> 00:24:39.270
exert their perceived control.

00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:41.600
So a palette of places
looks like this--

00:24:41.600 --> 00:24:44.540
you can go to your little
cafe in the front floor,

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:46.970
you can go to the long
tables where everybody

00:24:46.970 --> 00:24:48.950
is, you can go to
your private corral,

00:24:48.950 --> 00:24:50.850
you can book a meeting room.

00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:53.530
Most of the time in the
service of perceived control,

00:24:53.530 --> 00:24:56.470
there are more
seats than people.

00:24:56.470 --> 00:24:57.200
Why?

00:24:57.200 --> 00:24:59.140
Because, again, we want to
send the message of perceived

00:24:59.140 --> 00:25:00.680
control, that you
are free to roam.

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:02.680
How many of you
feel like you know

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:06.360
where you need to be when you're
doing certain types of work?

00:25:06.360 --> 00:25:09.200
But to restrict you
to just one place

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:12.520
limits your ability to sort of
exert that perceived control.

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:14.570
Some of the best offices
also organize around

00:25:14.570 --> 00:25:16.380
what we call neighborhoods.

00:25:16.380 --> 00:25:18.450
So there are certain
departmental neighborhoods,

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:20.866
and you know you're most likely
to find the colleagues you

00:25:20.866 --> 00:25:21.770
need to find there.

00:25:21.770 --> 00:25:24.510
But you also know that
if they're not there,

00:25:24.510 --> 00:25:26.440
presence and performance
aren't correlated.

00:25:26.440 --> 00:25:27.940
It doesn't mean
they're not working.

00:25:27.940 --> 00:25:30.148
It just means they're working
sort of somewhere else.

00:25:30.148 --> 00:25:32.580
We're putting it back in the
service of perceived control.

00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:36.400
One more, one of my
favorites, is the perf.

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:38.390
It's perf season, isn't it?

00:25:38.390 --> 00:25:40.200
Yeah, so let's talk about this.

00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:41.520
Let's talk about the perf.

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:43.580
I'll give you a very,
very brief story

00:25:43.580 --> 00:25:46.050
of a hugely innovative
company that sort of ditched

00:25:46.050 --> 00:25:48.310
the perf altogether,
that basically threw it

00:25:48.310 --> 00:25:50.050
in the trashcan,
and that's Adobe.

00:25:50.050 --> 00:25:52.880
Adobe, as you know, has moved
from that sort of products

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:55.480
boxes on the shelf, the way you
used to have to get Photoshop,

00:25:55.480 --> 00:25:58.150
to now Adobe Creative Cloud
and this idea of paying

00:25:58.150 --> 00:25:59.250
a subscription.

00:25:59.250 --> 00:26:01.060
And it triggered a
conversation about what

00:26:01.060 --> 00:26:03.040
are the other things
we're doing legacy

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:06.180
on a yearly cycle or a
six-month cycle, et cetera?

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:09.380
And they ended up taking a
deep look at their performance

00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:11.820
evaluations and deciding
to throw it in the trash.

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:13.770
Some of you may be wanting to
throw your perf in the trash

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:14.320
right now.

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:16.200
Others of you might like
it, and that's cool.

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:20.260
And I can tell you why both of
you feel the exact same way.

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:21.365
Why?

00:26:21.365 --> 00:26:23.990
In order to tell you why, let me
first tell you what Adobe did.

00:26:23.990 --> 00:26:26.830
They moved from the
performance appraisal system

00:26:26.830 --> 00:26:28.700
to a system of
expectations, feedback,

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:30.950
and growth and development
that they called check-ins.

00:26:30.950 --> 00:26:33.830
A check-in is any conversation--
can happen very frequently,

00:26:33.830 --> 00:26:37.294
can happen every few
months, mostly happens

00:26:37.294 --> 00:26:39.210
sort of on a monthly or
every six weeks basis,

00:26:39.210 --> 00:26:40.668
could take as little
as 10 minutes,

00:26:40.668 --> 00:26:42.400
can take as long as you want.

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:44.400
And it's centered around
expectations, feedback,

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:45.525
and growth and development.

00:26:45.525 --> 00:26:47.070
Expectations--
setting, tracking,

00:26:47.070 --> 00:26:49.080
reviewing what the
objectives are-- not only

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:51.140
what your objectives
are performance,

00:26:51.140 --> 00:26:55.340
but what your expectations
for me are if I'm the manager.

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:57.470
Feedback is the same
way-- giving and receiving

00:26:57.470 --> 00:26:59.156
ongoing feedback and coaching.

00:26:59.156 --> 00:27:00.530
And then growth
and development--

00:27:00.530 --> 00:27:01.529
where do you want to go?

00:27:01.529 --> 00:27:03.160
Talking about
opportunities-- how

00:27:03.160 --> 00:27:05.234
does your role fit into
the broader spectrum,

00:27:05.234 --> 00:27:06.400
and where do you want to go?

00:27:06.400 --> 00:27:10.210
What I think is great about the
check-in process is twofold,

00:27:10.210 --> 00:27:12.550
and why it works is twofold.

00:27:12.550 --> 00:27:15.290
First, we have perspective.

00:27:15.290 --> 00:27:20.430
We have this idea that
giving performance appraisals

00:27:20.430 --> 00:27:22.357
is vital, giving
feedback is vital,

00:27:22.357 --> 00:27:23.440
to increasing performance.

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:26.370
And that's true, but most
places do on an annual basis

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:29.650
or a six-month basis.

00:27:29.650 --> 00:27:31.460
And so most places
give that feedback.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:34.630
But imagine for a minute, like
the hypothetical example I use

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:38.110
is imagine you're a football
team and you play every Sunday.

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:39.780
And you're going to
play this Sunday,

00:27:39.780 --> 00:27:42.720
but we're not going to tell you
the score for six months, when

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:44.309
we do your next perf.

00:27:44.309 --> 00:27:46.725
How likely is that you can
make course corrections easily?

00:27:46.725 --> 00:27:48.280
Not that likely.

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:50.307
Feedback in the office
works the exact same way.

00:27:50.307 --> 00:27:52.890
The more frequently you can give
that perspective of feedback,

00:27:52.890 --> 00:27:54.348
the more frequently
you can iterate

00:27:54.348 --> 00:27:56.470
towards better performance.

00:27:56.470 --> 00:27:58.260
So we might normally
do an annual review.

00:27:58.260 --> 00:28:00.660
Some places go to six months.

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:02.470
But these one-on-one
informal discussions

00:28:02.470 --> 00:28:04.655
staged throughout
are hugely vital.

00:28:04.655 --> 00:28:06.530
Now, here's why I think
this is so important.

00:28:06.530 --> 00:28:09.100
Even though I know
it's perf season,

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:12.957
is that I normally only get to
have the ear of people in HR

00:28:12.957 --> 00:28:15.290
when I make my case for
ditching performance appraisals.

00:28:15.290 --> 00:28:17.250
But every single
person can learn

00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:20.500
from check-ins and one-on-one
informal discussions.

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:23.260
If you remember nothing else
other than the earbuds thing,

00:28:23.260 --> 00:28:26.100
maybe we can also add
on-- because by the way,

00:28:26.100 --> 00:28:27.600
rule three of
speaking is you're not

00:28:27.600 --> 00:28:29.599
supposed to say "if you
remember anything else,"

00:28:29.599 --> 00:28:31.880
so I'm going to leave
you with, like, four.

00:28:31.880 --> 00:28:36.930
So if you remember this, too--
expectations, feedback, growth

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:37.610
and development.

00:28:37.610 --> 00:28:40.800
Even if you have to do the perf
every six months, if you can

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:42.556
every week, every two
weeks, every month,

00:28:42.556 --> 00:28:44.930
have a conversation that
centers around those things that

00:28:44.930 --> 00:28:48.110
is frank and honest,
then when we arrive

00:28:48.110 --> 00:28:50.940
at the next formal
appraisal cycle,

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:53.620
we arrive at a conversation
that doesn't surprise anyone,

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:56.170
that doesn't create negotiations
over what your rank is

00:28:56.170 --> 00:28:58.700
and what your label
is or any of that.

00:28:58.700 --> 00:29:00.820
We just arrive at
one more conversation

00:29:00.820 --> 00:29:02.630
in an ever-continuous
improvement

00:29:02.630 --> 00:29:06.700
cycle of feedback, expectations,
and growth and development.

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:08.890
So that's performance
appraisals.

00:29:08.890 --> 00:29:11.316
Overall, because I want to
get some time to questions.

00:29:11.316 --> 00:29:13.440
I knew lots of people begged
me for the open office

00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:14.630
question, the perf
question, because that's

00:29:14.630 --> 00:29:16.770
where we are, at least
among the ones I surveyed.

00:29:16.770 --> 00:29:17.270
Who?

00:29:17.270 --> 00:29:18.936
You're not allowed
to know who they are.

00:29:18.936 --> 00:29:20.840
It might affect them.

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:24.669
But every time that I talk
about these ideas and every time

00:29:24.669 --> 00:29:26.710
that I talk about that
shift from industrial work

00:29:26.710 --> 00:29:29.690
to knowledge work and every
time I tell an HR or VP that you

00:29:29.690 --> 00:29:31.410
should ditch
performance appraisals,

00:29:31.410 --> 00:29:33.230
I get a very similar response.

00:29:33.230 --> 00:29:36.060
I either get love it or loathe
it, love it or loathe it.

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:39.126
And the loath-its always say,
we have no reason to change.

00:29:39.126 --> 00:29:40.500
What we're doing
here is working.

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:42.160
What we're doing
here is working.

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:43.430
Why change?

00:29:43.430 --> 00:29:46.070
And every time I hear that,
I think about the same thing.

00:29:46.070 --> 00:29:48.570
I think about the internal
combustion engine.

00:29:48.570 --> 00:29:49.070
Why?

00:29:49.070 --> 00:29:53.046
Because I'm a nerd, but
also because actually this

00:29:53.046 --> 00:29:54.670
is one of the rare
times I can ask this

00:29:54.670 --> 00:29:56.290
in the history of speaking.

00:29:56.290 --> 00:29:59.490
How many of you have studied
physics as an undergrad?

00:29:59.490 --> 00:30:00.200
Yes.

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:02.283
And what do you know about
the internal combustion

00:30:02.283 --> 00:30:04.850
engine and its ability to
take gasoline and transform it

00:30:04.850 --> 00:30:06.283
into forward motion?

00:30:06.283 --> 00:30:09.270
It's thermodynamics.

00:30:09.270 --> 00:30:10.720
It's very inefficient.

00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:13.990
It is 30% efficient.

00:30:13.990 --> 00:30:17.094
30% of the energy in
gasoline, in that fuel,

00:30:17.094 --> 00:30:19.010
gets actually transferred
into forward motion.

00:30:19.010 --> 00:30:20.551
The rest is lost to
heat and friction

00:30:20.551 --> 00:30:24.040
and the rules of
thermodynamics-- 30% efficient.

00:30:24.040 --> 00:30:25.740
And yet we experiment
with a lot of ways

00:30:25.740 --> 00:30:27.274
to make that more efficient.

00:30:27.274 --> 00:30:29.190
Whether that's putting
a new engine in the car

00:30:29.190 --> 00:30:33.410
or making the car self-driving,
we continue to experiment.

00:30:33.410 --> 00:30:34.800
The human engine
is no different.

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:37.100
The organization
is no different.

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:40.000
For most of us, the fuel
running most organizations

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.170
isn't brute labor and
it's not gasoline.

00:30:42.170 --> 00:30:44.450
It might be Red Bull,
but it's not gasoline.

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:46.299
It's mental energy.

00:30:46.299 --> 00:30:48.840
And when we talk about mental
energy, one of our best metrics

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:51.900
for measuring efficiency is the
employee engagement metrics,

00:30:51.900 --> 00:30:53.300
first made famous by Gallup.

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:55.254
But a variety of
different researchers

00:30:55.254 --> 00:30:56.670
use a variety of
different metrics

00:30:56.670 --> 00:30:58.970
all to try and say how
much of our whole selves

00:30:58.970 --> 00:31:01.220
are we bringing to work, how
much of our mental energy

00:31:01.220 --> 00:31:03.110
are we bringing to
work, how many people

00:31:03.110 --> 00:31:04.610
inside our organization
are bringing

00:31:04.610 --> 00:31:06.190
their whole selves to work?

00:31:06.190 --> 00:31:11.050
And what we find is worldwide,
the number's about 18%.

00:31:11.050 --> 00:31:14.420
It's worse than the
internal combustion engine.

00:31:14.420 --> 00:31:16.757
In the US, it's about 30%.

00:31:16.757 --> 00:31:18.090
And I suspect here, it's higher.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:20.380
But I've never met an
organization that even takes it

00:31:20.380 --> 00:31:23.960
to 50%, meaning that 50% of
the time or 50% of the people

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:27.370
feel like they bring their
whole mental energy to work.

00:31:27.370 --> 00:31:31.280
So why is it OK to continue
to experiment with an engine,

00:31:31.280 --> 00:31:33.060
but it's not OK to
continue to experiment

00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:35.360
with an organization?

00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:37.520
And that's my central
idea around this thesis.

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:40.200
What Frederick Taylor
did was he figured out

00:31:40.200 --> 00:31:41.920
how to optimize for
brute force and how

00:31:41.920 --> 00:31:43.860
to make it more efficient.

00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:46.080
And we drug a lot of
those principles with us

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:48.864
from the factory to the office.

00:31:48.864 --> 00:31:50.280
And suddenly now,
what we're doing

00:31:50.280 --> 00:31:53.360
is working, so it's not to
continue to question it.

00:31:53.360 --> 00:31:55.720
The leaders, the entrepreneurs,
the corporate leaders,

00:31:55.720 --> 00:31:58.250
the researchers that I profile
in "Under New Management"

00:31:58.250 --> 00:32:01.560
are all not satisfied
with the engine as usual.

00:32:01.560 --> 00:32:03.310
And honestly, not every
one of these ideas

00:32:03.310 --> 00:32:04.810
works for every
single organization.

00:32:04.810 --> 00:32:07.030
But every single one of
them is an experiment.

00:32:07.030 --> 00:32:08.019
It's a moonshot.

00:32:08.019 --> 00:32:09.560
It's an attempt to
raise this number.

00:32:09.560 --> 00:32:11.380
And I'm not an optimist.

00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:13.780
I don't believe that
we can get to 100%

00:32:13.780 --> 00:32:17.717
on the whatever is slightly less
depressed than an optimist--

00:32:17.717 --> 00:32:19.800
I'm not a pessimist, but
whatever is slightly less

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:21.270
depressed than an optimist.

00:32:21.270 --> 00:32:25.390
I don't believe that we can
get that number up to 100%.

00:32:25.390 --> 00:32:27.510
But, god, if we
could get it to 50%?

00:32:27.510 --> 00:32:29.580
If most Americans had
a coin-flip chance

00:32:29.580 --> 00:32:33.020
of finding a job that engaged
them, that'd be amazing.

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:33.720
I have two sons.

00:32:33.720 --> 00:32:36.290
They're four and they're two.

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:38.340
And this is honestly
what drives me

00:32:38.340 --> 00:32:42.340
around this, is that
I'm thinking about 15,

00:32:42.340 --> 00:32:45.090
20 years from now
where they go to work,

00:32:45.090 --> 00:32:47.660
can we change the engine
and get it to the point

00:32:47.660 --> 00:32:52.000
where they have a coin-flip
chance of being engaged?

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:53.770
Even an organization
that lots of people

00:32:53.770 --> 00:32:56.270
like to write about, like
Google, that you know people

00:32:56.270 --> 00:32:57.750
who are not bringing their
whole selves to work,

00:32:57.750 --> 00:32:58.499
can we experiment?

00:32:58.499 --> 00:33:00.010
Can we change these ideas?

00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:02.640
Can we play around with
new modes and methods

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:04.650
to raise this number up?

00:33:04.650 --> 00:33:06.490
Great leaders don't
innovate the product,

00:33:06.490 --> 00:33:08.439
they innovate the factory.

00:33:08.439 --> 00:33:09.980
So let's turn our
conversation to how

00:33:09.980 --> 00:33:11.730
we can innovate
the factory and let

00:33:11.730 --> 00:33:14.390
that be the huge
surge that proceeds

00:33:14.390 --> 00:33:16.020
a wave of product innovation.

00:33:16.020 --> 00:33:16.900
We can get there.

00:33:16.900 --> 00:33:17.460
We can.

00:33:17.460 --> 00:33:20.120
It just takes continued
experimentation.

00:33:20.120 --> 00:33:22.210
Great leaders don't
innovate the product,

00:33:22.210 --> 00:33:24.250
they innovate the factory.

00:33:24.250 --> 00:33:26.484
That said, what questions
do you have about how

00:33:26.484 --> 00:33:27.400
we innovate a factory?

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.870
AUDIENCE: So on the
open floor plan issue,

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:37.210
the book "Making Software"
cites sociology studies that

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:40.940
were put together on open
offices versus closed offices.

00:33:40.940 --> 00:33:44.170
And it basically came down to if
the task was an individual sort

00:33:44.170 --> 00:33:45.810
of task, closed doors help.

00:33:45.810 --> 00:33:49.270
If it's a collaborative task,
then having open space helps.

00:33:49.270 --> 00:33:51.980
Why do you cite it as just
individual preference?

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:54.230
DAVID BURKUS: So I think
it's a combination of things.

00:33:54.230 --> 00:33:56.090
I definitely think
it's the type of work.

00:33:56.090 --> 00:33:57.839
And most people, I
don't think you can say

00:33:57.839 --> 00:33:59.877
do one type of work one way.

00:33:59.877 --> 00:34:01.960
So I think there's a human
psychology piece, which

00:34:01.960 --> 00:34:03.501
is individual
differences, and then I

00:34:03.501 --> 00:34:05.750
think there's the type
of work that people do.

00:34:05.750 --> 00:34:08.471
But then even if you combine,
like you times those two

00:34:08.471 --> 00:34:09.929
by each other and
you have a factor

00:34:09.929 --> 00:34:12.155
a variety of different
things-- like I,

00:34:12.155 --> 00:34:14.280
because my training's in
organizational psychology,

00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:16.159
tend to lean towards that side.

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:19.100
But the type of work being
done also influences it.

00:34:19.100 --> 00:34:22.280
But there's a confounding factor
of how an individual likes

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:23.634
to do that type of work.

00:34:23.634 --> 00:34:24.300
So I'm a writer.

00:34:24.300 --> 00:34:26.258
And I know people that
love to write in solace,

00:34:26.258 --> 00:34:28.580
and I know people that will
deliberately go to a cafe

00:34:28.580 --> 00:34:30.460
in order to write with all
sorts of noise around them--

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:32.460
same type of work, but
the individual difference

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:35.100
is sort of also a
confounding factor in it.

00:34:35.100 --> 00:34:41.010
AUDIENCE: Should we focus more
on what environment fails less

00:34:41.010 --> 00:34:42.940
for the opposite task
when it comes up,

00:34:42.940 --> 00:34:45.674
and not the obvious fact
that open offices are better

00:34:45.674 --> 00:34:47.340
for collaboration and
closed offices are

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:50.800
better for independent work?

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:53.562
DAVID BURKUS: I side on the side
of perceived control, like I

00:34:53.562 --> 00:34:55.520
think when we need to
think about how we design

00:34:55.520 --> 00:34:56.860
a whole place, we need
to know that there's

00:34:56.860 --> 00:34:58.870
a ton of different types of
work and a ton of different ways

00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:00.578
that people like to
do that type of work.

00:35:00.578 --> 00:35:02.260
And so that palette
of places approach

00:35:02.260 --> 00:35:04.160
gives perceived control
over to the person.

00:35:04.160 --> 00:35:06.430
It gives them the
individual idea.

00:35:06.430 --> 00:35:09.160
That does mean we have to have
a conversation about how you can

00:35:09.160 --> 00:35:11.530
know whether or not you're being
productive because sometimes we

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:13.155
might feel like we're
being productive,

00:35:13.155 --> 00:35:15.750
but we're actually being
distracted often-- see email

00:35:15.750 --> 00:35:16.816
as an example.

00:35:16.816 --> 00:35:18.190
But I think, again,
it comes down

00:35:18.190 --> 00:35:19.856
to that idea of
designing the place that

00:35:19.856 --> 00:35:21.570
works for a variety
of different means

00:35:21.570 --> 00:35:25.820
and then just setting people
free to kind of figure it out.

00:35:25.820 --> 00:35:27.879
AUDIENCE: So performance--

00:35:27.879 --> 00:35:28.670
DAVID BURKUS: Yeah.

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:29.910
AUDIENCE: We all hate it.

00:35:29.910 --> 00:35:30.910
And one of the reasons--

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:31.840
DAVID BURKUS:
Performance appraisals.

00:35:31.840 --> 00:35:32.955
AUDIENCE: Performance
appraisals,

00:35:32.955 --> 00:35:33.865
not high performance.

00:35:33.865 --> 00:35:35.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:35.230 --> 00:35:35.650
DAVID BURKUS: I
was going to say,

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:37.520
I think I'm in the wrong
room if that's the case.

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:38.394
AUDIENCE: Perf, perf.

00:35:38.394 --> 00:35:39.750
DAVID BURKUS: Perf, right.

00:35:39.750 --> 00:35:40.910
AUDIENCE: We all hate it.

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:42.899
And one of the
reasons I hate it is--

00:35:42.899 --> 00:35:45.190
DAVID BURKUS: You're saying
this on camera, by the way.

00:35:45.190 --> 00:35:47.130
I was deliberately not asking
questions about this one.

00:35:47.130 --> 00:35:47.490
AUDIENCE: That's fine.

00:35:47.490 --> 00:35:47.810
DAVID BURKUS: No, no.

00:35:47.810 --> 00:35:48.760
Go for it.

00:35:48.760 --> 00:35:51.820
AUDIENCE: There's a
tension between being

00:35:51.820 --> 00:35:54.710
honest and playing the game.

00:35:54.710 --> 00:35:57.210
So when I'm talking
to my boss, I really

00:35:57.210 --> 00:35:58.880
don't want to tell
him, you know what?

00:35:58.880 --> 00:36:01.700
Monday and Tuesday this
week, I got nothing done.

00:36:01.700 --> 00:36:05.190
And I'm in a bad mood,
and I hate my co-worker.

00:36:05.190 --> 00:36:07.610
And by the way, you made
a stupid mistake yesterday

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:11.220
at the meeting, which completely
derailed, blah, blah, blah.

00:36:11.220 --> 00:36:13.400
Do I really want to
say things like that?

00:36:13.400 --> 00:36:17.500
And how is the continuous
process any better?

00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:22.727
My boss is not my therapist, and
can influence my career, right?

00:36:22.727 --> 00:36:23.560
DAVID BURKUS: Right.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:25.820
AUDIENCE: So how do you
deal with this tension

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:29.660
between honesty and a
productive feedback?

00:36:29.660 --> 00:36:32.604
DAVID BURKUS: So the first
challenge is, other than--

00:36:32.604 --> 00:36:34.770
and actually, your comment
reminded me of that scene

00:36:34.770 --> 00:36:36.640
in "Office Space" where he
describes what he does and he's

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:38.098
like, I get to work
and I just kind

00:36:38.098 --> 00:36:39.976
of stare at the wall
for, like, 15 minutes.

00:36:39.976 --> 00:36:42.226
So you don't want to admit
that, although he admits it

00:36:42.226 --> 00:36:44.100
and he gets promoted.

00:36:44.100 --> 00:36:47.751
The things that you said my boss
doesn't kind of want to hear,

00:36:47.751 --> 00:36:49.250
part of him doesn't
want to hear it.

00:36:49.250 --> 00:36:53.339
Part of him needs to hear it,
or part of her needs to hear it.

00:36:53.339 --> 00:36:55.380
And so it begins from that
place of understanding

00:36:55.380 --> 00:36:58.616
that these sessions aren't
necessary be used to label.

00:36:58.616 --> 00:37:00.490
They're to be used to
have that conversation,

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:02.150
and it takes an
openness at that level

00:37:02.150 --> 00:37:03.820
to actually hear that feedback.

00:37:03.820 --> 00:37:04.920
Now, for some people,
it takes a lot

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:06.461
of training to get
them to that point

00:37:06.461 --> 00:37:09.297
where they're sort of open
to hearing that feedback.

00:37:09.297 --> 00:37:11.130
One of my writer friends
say teaching people

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:13.588
how to hug their haters so they
can actually learn and grow

00:37:13.588 --> 00:37:14.230
from it.

00:37:14.230 --> 00:37:17.330
The biggest thing is the lack
of formality of the event.

00:37:17.330 --> 00:37:19.940
I think what causes
a lot of the stress

00:37:19.940 --> 00:37:21.800
and the playing the
game that you said

00:37:21.800 --> 00:37:24.650
is that it eventually gets
documented, goes in a file.

00:37:24.650 --> 00:37:26.640
And so it's very
careful about what

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:29.800
goes in the file, what
doesn't go in the file.

00:37:29.800 --> 00:37:33.240
And a lot of times, it'll take
some time to ramp up to it.

00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:34.720
But when you can
sort of actually

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:36.261
get people to believe
that, no, we're

00:37:36.261 --> 00:37:38.310
having an open, honest
conversation, none of it's

00:37:38.310 --> 00:37:39.726
getting written
down, none of it's

00:37:39.726 --> 00:37:41.930
going in a file,
let's just talk,

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:44.044
gradually people start
to lower their guard.

00:37:44.044 --> 00:37:45.460
It will not happen
the first time.

00:37:45.460 --> 00:37:47.540
Like I said, I'm one
step below optimism.

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:50.280
Whatever is one step less
pessimistic than an optimist,

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:51.150
I'm that.

00:37:51.150 --> 00:37:52.740
So it won't happen right away.

00:37:52.740 --> 00:37:54.640
But the hope is that
if we shift to that

00:37:54.640 --> 00:37:57.541
and we really get people
to believe that these are

00:37:57.541 --> 00:37:59.790
informal conversations,
they're not going in the file,

00:37:59.790 --> 00:38:01.954
they're just about how do
we get you what you need,

00:38:01.954 --> 00:38:03.370
then we can actually
move towards.

00:38:03.370 --> 00:38:07.880
AUDIENCE: As a fairly quick
followup, we do have procedures

00:38:07.880 --> 00:38:10.700
here where you can ask
for advice from someone

00:38:10.700 --> 00:38:14.830
outside your management
chain, which I haven't taken

00:38:14.830 --> 00:38:17.350
advantage of enough, I'm sure.

00:38:17.350 --> 00:38:20.080
Does it make sense
for the same person

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:24.300
to be managing you day-to-day
and evaluating you and getting

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:25.450
honest feedback?

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:28.130
Are those all the same role?

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:29.630
DAVID BURKUS: It varies a lot.

00:38:29.630 --> 00:38:31.830
So one of the
chapters that, which

00:38:31.830 --> 00:38:34.312
I didn't go into it today, but
one of the chapters we have

00:38:34.312 --> 00:38:36.520
in "Under New Management"
is about the companies that

00:38:36.520 --> 00:38:38.054
really do fire the manager.

00:38:38.054 --> 00:38:39.470
And then there are
other companies

00:38:39.470 --> 00:38:41.400
to try and do it and find
that they need a management

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:41.760
structure.

00:38:41.760 --> 00:38:44.260
And it comes down to there are
certain roles in management

00:38:44.260 --> 00:38:46.410
in every organization
based on the type of work

00:38:46.410 --> 00:38:49.484
and the culture can decide
who best does those role.

00:38:49.484 --> 00:38:51.650
And sometimes, they decide
the team works it better,

00:38:51.650 --> 00:38:52.762
the peers do it better.

00:38:52.762 --> 00:38:54.970
Sometimes they decide that
management does it better.

00:38:54.970 --> 00:38:55.790
But you're absolutely right.

00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:58.270
One of the things I love
about in the accountability

00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:01.567
piece around doing
360 for management

00:39:01.567 --> 00:39:03.650
was that idea that everybody
who's interacted your

00:39:03.650 --> 00:39:05.210
throughout the year
has that ability

00:39:05.210 --> 00:39:08.410
to leave you feedback, which
I think it's hard, again,

00:39:08.410 --> 00:39:10.490
do that in an
informal conversation.

00:39:10.490 --> 00:39:12.829
That said, the hope
and the assumption

00:39:12.829 --> 00:39:14.870
is that your manager and
the people on your team,

00:39:14.870 --> 00:39:16.411
the people who work
closest with you,

00:39:16.411 --> 00:39:18.970
are the most invested in
your long-term success,

00:39:18.970 --> 00:39:20.590
your long-term performance.

00:39:20.590 --> 00:39:22.500
And so because of that
emotional investment,

00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:24.790
they're probably the best one to
have the informal conversation

00:39:24.790 --> 00:39:25.540
with.

00:39:25.540 --> 00:39:26.680
But you're absolutely
right, most of us

00:39:26.680 --> 00:39:29.000
work with people who are
not technically on our team,

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:30.833
and we still collaborate
with them at times.

00:39:30.833 --> 00:39:32.450
And that data isn't
really getting

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:33.971
captured in a very good system.

00:39:33.971 --> 00:39:36.220
Some of that's the nature
of the beast, and some of it

00:39:36.220 --> 00:39:38.700
is we shouldn't
allow it to happen.

00:39:38.700 --> 00:39:39.922
We should spread it out.

00:39:39.922 --> 00:39:40.630
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:41.739
DAVID BURKUS: Thank you.

00:39:41.739 --> 00:39:42.280
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:42.280 --> 00:39:43.930
So thank you for the talks.

00:39:43.930 --> 00:39:46.362
So staying on this
topic, so getting rid

00:39:46.362 --> 00:39:47.820
of performance
evaluations-- I want

00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:49.920
to look under the cover
of that a little bit.

00:39:49.920 --> 00:39:52.170
DAVID BURKUS: Everybody
wants-- it's the right season.

00:39:52.170 --> 00:39:53.440
AUDIENCE: It reminds
me of politicians

00:39:53.440 --> 00:39:55.160
who say that we should get
rid of the Internal Revenue

00:39:55.160 --> 00:39:55.660
Service.

00:39:55.660 --> 00:39:57.490
That sound
superficially appealing.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:40:01.310
But at the end of the day, those
things still need to get done.

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:05.482
And so in my past many
years of being a manager,

00:40:05.482 --> 00:40:07.440
I've come to realize that
a lot of this process

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:09.440
is not about torturing
the individual employees.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:12.500
It's really about forcing
managers to do the right thing.

00:40:12.500 --> 00:40:14.860
So without things like
curves, for example,

00:40:14.860 --> 00:40:18.800
you'll have lazy managers who
give everyone the same score.

00:40:18.800 --> 00:40:21.410
They're conflict-averse, or
they'll just give the bennies

00:40:21.410 --> 00:40:22.800
to their friends or whatever.

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:25.039
And so we need sort of
the managers' managers

00:40:25.039 --> 00:40:27.330
kind of structure to make
sure the right things happen.

00:40:27.330 --> 00:40:28.570
And that has to happen,
anyway, I think.

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:30.650
So to me, it feels
like a false dichotomy.

00:40:30.650 --> 00:40:32.900
It's not really get rid of
the performance evaluation,

00:40:32.900 --> 00:40:34.420
it's really you need both.

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:37.670
A good manager should be
doing those other things

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:38.890
all the time, anyway.

00:40:38.890 --> 00:40:40.390
But you still need
a formal process.

00:40:40.390 --> 00:40:42.860
You still need a process
to compare people

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:43.740
in an objective way.

00:40:43.740 --> 00:40:46.300
You still need to decide
about promotions and raises

00:40:46.300 --> 00:40:49.552
and who was not performing
and so on and so forth.

00:40:49.552 --> 00:40:50.260
DAVID BURKUS: No.

00:40:50.260 --> 00:40:51.780
And so in general, I agree.

00:40:51.780 --> 00:40:54.240
So there's a teeny bit of
hyperbole to get rid of the IRS

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:56.372
because it's always if
deep down, we're going

00:40:56.372 --> 00:40:57.580
to replace it with something.

00:40:57.580 --> 00:41:00.310
Or it's not, and
hopefully that person

00:41:00.310 --> 00:41:02.120
doesn't get a
plurality of the vote.

00:41:02.120 --> 00:41:06.770
But so it's always a
situation where you're

00:41:06.770 --> 00:41:08.000
replacing it with something.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:09.520
In this case, I love
the Adobe example

00:41:09.520 --> 00:41:10.936
because what they
replaced it with

00:41:10.936 --> 00:41:14.092
was we're going to get
rid of this formal system.

00:41:14.092 --> 00:41:16.050
And one of the things I
sort of didn't roll out

00:41:16.050 --> 00:41:18.175
is we're going to replace
it with coaching managers

00:41:18.175 --> 00:41:19.757
and have these
conversations, when

00:41:19.757 --> 00:41:22.090
to have these conversations,
a lot of different training

00:41:22.090 --> 00:41:22.846
on it.

00:41:22.846 --> 00:41:24.720
And that can only really
happen in a culture,

00:41:24.720 --> 00:41:26.300
too, that reinforces
those ideas--

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:28.000
that feedback, that
evaluation, that

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:31.170
keeping track of who
needs what in order to be

00:41:31.170 --> 00:41:33.841
ready for promotions, et
cetera, is hugely important.

00:41:33.841 --> 00:41:36.090
So you can't just sort of
strip it, you're absolutely.

00:41:36.090 --> 00:41:38.690
What you can do is train
that informal system.

00:41:38.690 --> 00:41:41.760
